  "script": "Too many koalas? It sounds impossible, but in parts of South Australia there are now so many koalas that the forests literally cannot feed them all. Here's the trap: koalas basically only eat eucalyptus leaves. Pack too many koalas into one patch of trees, and they strip the branches bare faster than the leaves can grow back. The trees start dying. And once the food runs out, the same population boom that looked adorable turns into mass starvation. Wildlife officials are now stuck with brutal choices — move them, sterilize them, or let nature crash. A cuddly icon has quietly become an ecological time bomb. So what do you actually do when the koala becomes the threat?",
